cantos should be regarded as having separate functions (e.g., I = prologue to the poem as a \softline
whole, II = prologue to the first }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), E.H. Wilkins ("The Prologue of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Divine Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Annual Report of the Dante Society}{\plain \fs24 \f1  42 [1926], 1-7) argues, on the basis of discussion of the \softline
defining characteristics of prologues found in the Epistle to Cangrande (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epist}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIII.43-48), that \softline
cantos I and II form a unitary prologue to the entire poem as well as to its first canticle.  This \softline
reader finds his comments just and convincing.  Once again we observe that commentators, \softline
following earlier commentators rather than the text of the poem, create interpretive artifacts (here, \softline
the notion that the two cantos have separate functions) that then take on, by virtue of repetition, \softline
the appearance of being Dantean 'facts.'  In actuality, all three }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantiche}{\plain \fs24 \f1  begin with two-canto-long \softline
