}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Florence: \softline
Sansoni, 1967),  pp. 165-166.  These three lines, as has often been noted, have a sad eloquence \softline
that establishes a mode of writing to which the poet will return when he considers the Virgilian \softline
'tears of things' in the lives of some of his characters.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The protagonist, about to descend into hell, is described, perhaps surprisingly, since he \softline
is in the company of Virgil, as being alone ('sol uno').  But see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.xxvi.9, where Dante \softline
describes Aeneas, about to begin his descent }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ad inferos}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , similarly as being 'alone': '...quando esso \softline
Enea sostenette }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 solo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  con Sibilla a entrare ne lo Inferno.'  In Dante's view, it would seem that the \softline
condition of a mortal soul, about to enter the underworld, is one of loneliness, even though it is \softline
accompanied by a shade.  See Hollander, "Le opere di Virgilio nella }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  di Dante," in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante e la "bella scola" della poesia: Autorit{\f3 \'42} e sfida poetica}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. A. A. Iannucci (Ravenna: \softline
Longo, 1993), p. 256.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 4-5.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This formulation perhaps refers to the struggle of the protagonist with the difficulties \softline
of proceeding (his struggles with fearsome exterior forces ranged against him, from the three \softline
beasts in the first canto to Satan in the last) and with his own interior weakness, demonstrated by \softline
his occasional surrender to the emotion of pity (beginning with Francesca in the fifth canto and \softline
ending when he does not yield to Ugolino's entreaties for Dante's pity in the thirty-third).  For a \softline
possible five-part program that marks the development of the protagonist's strength, as he moves \softline
through five cycles of pity and fear in hell, see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
(Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1969), pp. 301-7.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 6.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   In the words of Singleton's gloss (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.6), 'Memory will now faithfully \softline
retrace the real event of the journey, exactly as it took place.  This most extraordinary journey \softline
through the three realms of the afterlife is represented, never as dreamed or experienced in vision, \softline
but as a real happening....  Here, then, and in the following invocation, the poet's voice is heard \softline
for the first time as it speaks of his task as poet.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The passage including the poem's first invocation is challenging and has caused \softline
serious interpretive difficulty.  Why does Dante invoke the Muses in a Christian work?  What \softline
does }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alto ingegno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (lofty genius) refer to?  Is the invocation of two powers ('Muses' and 'lofty \softline
genius') or of three (the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mente}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , or 'memory,' of verse 9)?  For a discussion of these points see \softline
Hollander, "The 'Canto of the Word' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2)," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Newberryana}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. P. Cherchi \softline
and A. C. Mastrobuono, vol. II (Evanston: Northwestern University Press, 1990), pp. 98-100.  \softline
The positions taken there have it that the 'muses' are the devices of poetic making that the \softline
individual poet may master (see Grandgent, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II, Introduction: 'Dante probably \softline
believed that the Muses, even to the ancients, were only a figure of speech, a metaphor for poetic \softline
inspiration or art; so in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 VN}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXV.9 he says that Horace, calling upon the Muse, "parla... alla sua \softline
scienza medesima"' [speaks... to his own capacities]), that the 'lofty genius' is not Dante's, but \softline
God's, and that only these two elements are invoked, while 'mente' is merely put forward as \softline
having been effective in recording the facts of the journey (and is surely not 'invoked,' as the very \softline
language of the passage makes plain).  In this formulation, here and in some of his later \softline
invocations Dante is asking for divine assistance in conceptualizing the matter of his poem so that \softline
it may resemble his Creator, its source, while also asking for the help of the 'muses' in finding the \softline
most appropriate expressive techniques for that conceptualization.  Thus he is asking for God's \softline
help in shaping the vision and that of the 'muses' in making it rhyme, deploy compelling tropes, \softline
etc.  As for the raw content, that he has through his own experience; he requires no external aid \softline
for it.  What he does need is conceptual and expressive power, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alto ingegno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 arte}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
represented by the 'muses.'  It is worth noting that }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ingegno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 arte}{\plain \fs24 \f1  are joined in four later \softline
passages in the poem, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.125, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVII.130, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  X.43, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIV.117.  For a study of \softline
the meaning of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ingegno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in its 27 appearances (twice as the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ingegnare}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) in the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Paul Arvisu Dumol, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Metaphysics of Reading Underlying Dante's \softline
"Commedia": The }{\plain \fs24 \i\ul\f1 Ingegno}{\plain \fs24 \b\i\f1  }{\plain \fs24 \f1 (New York: Peter Lang, 1998).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab It is, given Dante's fondness for the number of Beatrice, nine, difficult to believe that the \softline
