}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 27.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This verse concludes the 'imperial theme' of this canto, initiated in v. 13.  These five 
tercets continually break Aeneas' identity or task into two aspects ('e 'l chi e 'l quale' [v. 18], 'de \softline
l'alma Roma e di suo impero' [v. 20], 'la quale e 'l quale' [v. 22], 'di sua vittoria e del papale \softline
ammanto' [v. 27].)  This speech is not in the mouth of Virgil, but of Dante, and for a reason.  It \softline
purveys, with some heated enthusiasm, the view of Roman imperial excellence that Dante had \softline
probably only recently developed.  He cannot allow its religious dimension utterance by Virgil, \softline
whose credentials as 'Christian' are not exactly imposing.  And so the not-very-mature protagonist \softline
is here given the author's voice to say what that author wants most definitely to set down before \softline
us.  And it is probably for this reason that the passage is as repetitive as it is.  There can be no \softline
mistaking what it says.\par
