'Canto of the Word' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Newberryana}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. P. Cherchi and A. C. \softline
Mastrobuono, vol. II [Evanston: Northwestern University Press, 1990], p. 103), at least when \softline
compared with the biblical authority enjoyed by Paul's.  And see the previous remark of \softline
Grandgent (comm. to}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II, Introduction): 'It is worth noting that in introducing the example of \softline
Aeneas, Dante begins with "tu dici che... ," and a few lines further on he uses the phrase "questa \softline
andata onde gli dai tu vanto"; so in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . 15.26, referring to the same episode, he adds "se fede \softline
merta nostra maggior Musa" (if our greatest "Muse" is worthy our belief), meaning Virgil.  These \softline
expressions seem to imply a mental reservation with regard to the literal veracity of Aeneas's \softline
adventure.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab With regard to the question of whether or not Dante believed Paul had been to hell (as \softline
recounted in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Visio Pauli}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) see Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.28, with bibliography [to which now \softline
