without her intervention he would have known nothing (the damned, we learn at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.100-108, \softline
do not know the present state of things on earth), done nothing.  Virgil's actions are thus so \softline
circumscribed that we can hardly miss Dante's point.  It is Beatrice in Heaven, not Virgil in \softline
Limbo, who is first aware of Dante's plight (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.49-51).  And the burden of Virgil's words here 
is to give testimony to the power and glory of Beatrice, to whose charge he immediately consigns \softline
himself.  It is she, not he, who initiates the action of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , something we did not know a \softline
canto ago (for an appreciation of Virgil's limited understanding of Beatrice, see Singleton, "Virgil \softline
Recognizes Beatrice," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Annual Report of the Dante Society}{\plain \fs24 \f1  74 [1956], pp. 32-33)' (cited from \softline
Hollander, "The 'Canto of the Word' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Newberryana}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. P. Cherchi \softline
