}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 56-57.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil describes Beatrice's words as being }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 soave e piana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (gentle and clear).  She \softline
will, in turn, describe his speech as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 parola ornata}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (polished words -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.67).  The two \softline
adjectives, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 piana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ornata}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , may remind us of a major distinction, found in medieval \softline
categorizations of rhetorical styles, between the plain, or low, style, and the ornate, or high.  \softline
Benvenuto (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.56) was the first to point this out, glossing 'soave e piana' as follows: \softline
'divine speech is sweet and humble, not elevated and proud, as it that of Virgil and the poets.'  \softline
Thus Virgil's description of Beatrice's words corresponds antithetically to hers of his; her speech \softline
represents the sublimely humble style valorized by the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , while his recalls the high style that \softline
marked pagan eloquence (the observation is drawn from Hollander, "The 'Canto of the Word' \softline
[}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Newberryana}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. P. Cherchi and A. C. Mastrobuono, vol. II \softline
[Evanston: Northwestern University Press, 1990], p. 107, where there are references to previous \softline
