}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.609 behind Dante's line.  His view is now widely accepted.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 60.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This is perhaps the most debated line of the canto.  Is the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mondo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (world) or \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 moto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (movement)?  In recent years the two 'sides' are represented by Pagliaro (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Ulisse}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ricerche \softline
semantiche sulla "Divina Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Messina-Florence: D'Anna, 1967]), p. 737, arguing for \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 moto}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , and Petrocchi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Introduzione), pp. 166-67, (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La \softline
Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), p. 28, arguing for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mondo}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  See the full review of \softline
the problem in Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" \softline
--Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]),  pp. 253-55, arguing convincingly for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mondo}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  But now \softline
see Lanza (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La Commed{\f3 \'58}a: nuovo testo critico secondo i pi{\f3 \'6a} antichi manoscritti fiorentini}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Anzio: \softline
De Rubeis, 1995]), p. 18, in support of Pagliaro's thesis, without, perhaps, taking Mazzoni's \softline
arguments sufficiently into account.  In his discussion of the verse, Mazzoni's main point is that \softline
the Virgilian passage that lies behind Dante's phrasing here is far more likely to be }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.607-609 (already cited only a line earlier at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.59 [see discussion in the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.58-60]) than \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.173-175, previously translated by Dante in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.iii.10.  The first of these 
passages would require us to understand }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mondo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as the most likely paraphrase; the second, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 moto}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 61.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For a consideration of the fullest implications of this verse, see Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Saggio di un \softline
