}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 74.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beatrice's promise to speak well of Virgil to God has drawn some skeptical response, \softline
e.g., Castelvetro: 'Questo che monta a Virgilio che {\f3 \'50} dannato?' (What good is this to Virgil, who \softline
is damned? -- comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.74).  We are probably meant to be more impressed than that.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 76-78.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The meaning of this difficult tercet would seem to be: 'O lady of virtuous \softline
disposition that alone, shared by others, may bring them, too, to salvation out of this sub-lunar \softline
world of sin....'  This is to rely on Mazzoni's affirmation (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Saggio di un nuovo commento alla \softline
"Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967], pp. 276-77) of Barbi's \softline
reading of the verse (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Sansoni, 1934], p. 22).  Barbi's (and \softline
Mazzoni's) main objection to making }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 donna}{\plain \fs24 \f1  the antecedent of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cui}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is that to do so 'depersonalizes' \softline
Beatrice, making her an 'allegory' of theology, as indeed most of the commentators who so \softline
construe the line do in fact interpret her.  Anna Maria Chiavacci Leonardi ("Questioni di \softline
punteggiatura in due celebri attacchi danteschi [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ., II 76-78 e X 67-69]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lettere Italiane}{\plain \fs24 \f1  36 \softline
[1984], pp. 4-19, mounts a sustained counter-attack upon the Barbi/Mazzoni position, citing \softline
Boethius (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Consolatio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.iii.3), who addresses the Lady Philosophy as 'omnium magistra virtutum' \softline
(mistress of every virtue), a passage first adduced by Pietro di Dante (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.76).  For 
her, as for Singleton ("Virgil Recognizes Beatrice," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Annual Report of the Dante Society}{\plain \fs24 \f1  74 \softline
[1956]) before her, the reference of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cui}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 donna}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , for Virgil that woman who knows all things, \softline
Philosophy.  Jacoff and Stephany (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Americana: "Inferno" II}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Philadelphia: \softline
University of Pennsylvania Press, 1989]), pp. 42-48, support Singleton and Chiavacci Leonardi.  \softline
What complicates any attempt at interpreting this verse is the fact that it is }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Virgil}{\plain \fs24 \f1  who is \softline
describing his meeting with Beatrice, a woman whom he does not know.  However, he perhaps \softline
knows enough to understand her extraordinary powers.  She has named herself at v. 70, \softline
announces (rather obliquely) that she inhabits heaven, and, that, when she returns there, she will \softline
praise him to God (vv. 71-74).  Virgil, having seen Christ harrow hell (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.52-63), knows that \softline
this woman, unlike any others whom he knew when he was on earth, is part of that Christian \softline
dispensation which alone permits the ascent to heaven.  Thus he knows all that he needs to in \softline
order to understand that the virtues of this woman are such that all those who share them may be \softline
saved  -- it is in these alone that the human race 'exceeds' its circumstances.  To make Beatrice \softline
unique among humankind would imply that no one but she 'exceeds' the dross of the physical \softline
universe.  And that would go too far, even for Dante.  Our translation follows Petrocchi, who also \softline
accepts the Barbi/Mazzoni reading of the line's meaning.  We also agree with that reading, while \softline
admitting that a strong case for the other view has been made by those who do not do so.\par
