}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 85-93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beatrice's insistence that she is not 'touchable' by the grim powers of the pains of \softline
hell underlines the marginality of sin for the saved.  Hell is simply not of concern to them.  It is \softline
important to know, as one begins reading the poem, what one can only know once one has \softline
finished it: no soul in purgation or in grace in heaven has a thought for the damned (only the \softline
damned themselves do).  Their concern for those who do not share their redeeming penitence or \softline
bliss is reserved for those still alive on earth, who have at least the hope of salvation.  Hell, for the \softline
saved, is a sordid reality of which it is better not to speak.  A similar disregard for the damned 
(and even for our mortal hero, wrestling with his sins) is evidenced by the wryly laconic and \softline
unsympathetic angel who descends to help Virgil lead his charge into the City of Dis (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.91-103).  Those who admire various of Dante's sinners, despite their eternal damnation, would do \softline
well to keep both these scenes in mind.  See the strong statements to this effect found in \softline
Grandgent{\u8219\'27}s article "}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Quid Ploras}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  118 (2000 [1926]), pp. 85-94; Grandgent \softline
reminds his reader of the harsh question put by the angel to St. Paul, who has allowed himself to \softline
weep for the damned, in the apocryphal }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Visio Pauli}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  The angel wants to know why Paul is \softline
weeping ("Quid ploras?") for the damned when his attention should be turned to Christ.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
