}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 105.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   What exactly does it mean, Lucy's insistence to Beatrice that, for her sake, Dante \softline
'left the vulgar herd' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 la volgare schiera}{\plain \fs24 \f1 )?  Guido da Pisa (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.105) interprets the \softline
phrase to mean Dante turned in his studies from the liberal arts to theology.  Without debating \softline
such a judgment, one might add a poetic dimension to it, as has Francesco Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Saggio di un \softline
nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]),  \softline
pp. 289-93.  According to him, the most important meaning of the verse is to reflect Dante's \softline
turning from a 'conventional' amorous poetic subject matter to what he will later call the 'dolce stil \softline
novo' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIV.57), a poetry that presents, in a new 'style,' the higher meaning of Beatrice.  \softline
(Some would go still farther and suggest that this meaning is essentially Christological -- see \softline
Hollander, "Dante's 'dolce stil novo' and the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante: mito e poesia. Atti del secondo 
Seminario dantesco internazionale, }{\plain \fs24 \f1 ed. M. Picone and T. Crivelli [Florence: Cesati, 1999], pp. \softline
263-81.)  Mazzoni's view is seconded by the importance of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 volgare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to Dante.  While it is \softline
surely at times limited to the negative sense of the Latin }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 vulgus}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , pertaining to the common people, \softline
the 'mob,' it is also the word that he uses to describe his own vernacular speech, as in the title of \softline
his treatise }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 De vulgari Eloquentia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ('On Eloquence in the Vernacular').  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The view that Dante's sense of his own poetic vocation is central to the meaning of this \softline
verse is supported by the text at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.101, where the group of classical poets, who so \softline
graciously include Dante in their number, is also described as a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 schiera}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (company).  Such a \softline
formulation of poetic filiation and denial of same results in the following view: In the second \softline
canto Dante tells of having left behind rhymers in the vernacular who sing centrally or only of \softline
sexual love; in the fourth he relates that he was included in a group of the greatest poets of all \softline
time, who dealt with more 'serious' matters.  These are the only two times in the work that the \softline
word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 schiera}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is used (or is possibly used, in the first case) for groups of poets.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Roberto Mercuri links this verse to Dante's earlier and similar disgust with the 'vulgar herd' \softline
expressed in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.i.8 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.i.10, where Dante, turning to the study of philosophy, \softline
describes those lesser men -- whom he now intends to aid by bringing them word of the \softline
philosophic truths that have been revealed to him -- as up to now partaking, not of his grand feast \softline
(a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , or banquet), but of grass and acorns in their }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 bestiale pastura}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (bestial feeding), and \softline
goes on to describe himself precisely as having escaped from such }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 pastura del vulgo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (feeding of \softline
the common folk).  See Mercuri, "Il canto II dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 L'Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1  11 (1998), p. 19.  \softline
However, the whole enterprise of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is pretty clearly aimed at less than theological \softline
speculation and is addressed to a specifically non-Beatricean woman (the 'Lady Philosophy').  And \softline
thus one might, with better reason, see this verse as correcting that earlier account of Dante's \softline
'breaking away' from the wrong sort of intellectual and amorous life to a better version.  In this \softline
mode, one might notice that the project of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is described as an attempt to slake our \softline
'natural thirst' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 la naturale sete}{\plain \fs24 \f1  -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.i.9) for philosophic knowing.  The next time we hear \softline
this phrase (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.1-3) it is restored to its source in John's gospel (John 4:5-15): the truth \softline
that is found alone in Christ.  In such ways Dante corrects some of his earlier opinions and \softline
judgments when he chooses to encounter them again in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 107-108.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As tormented a passage as may be found in this canto, and one of the most \softline
